title: For Sale:  CZ Custom/CGW SP-01 Tactical, Competition sights, Custom trigger, over $1100 invested
postcontent:
Cajun Gun Works full trigger parts package. 85 combat trigger. Extended firing pin. Reduced power firing pin block lifter spring, CGW lifter, reduced power mainspring, reduced power firing pin spring, short reset disconnector, CGW thin aluminum grips, CZ Custom comp rear sight (ramped, non painted plain black), CZ comp hammer, CZ Custom front fiber optic sight. 

This pistol was bought 1.5 months ago. All CGW parts were installed and function tested with 150 rnds of Federal 124gr ball. Functioned flawlessly. All original parts will be included. Original case, paperwork, and a genuine CZ belt/paddle holster is included(simple retention holster). Pistol is in fantastic shape. Even racking the slide, you can tell the pistol hasn't seen many rounds and isn't even broken in. 2-18rnd mags included. Pistol brush etc. 

Similarly upgraded CZ pistols such as the SDP's/Target lines go for well over $1400-1800. If you've ever shot a CZ, you know their triggers could be improved.  This pistol has a fantastic trigger and is by far the most accurate pistol I own. 
DA/SA pull weights have not been measured as I don't have a gauge. CGW's site says DA drops from 17lbs to 9. It feels like 6-7lb to me. CGW parts didn't adjust SA pull weight but the shortened reach and over/pre travel stops in combination with the race hammer makes for a fantastic SA. 
Recent personal issues have come up and this has got to go. As you can see this pistol is in new shape. Not interested in any trades at the moment. Cash and preferred FTF but will ship where possible. Must be 21, bring your drivers license and fill out a bill of sale. Meet in SE PDX off 82nd. 

First person to meet the above requirements and hand me $900 gets a deal.  I initially agreed to send this pistol out but will no longer do so considering the amount of local interest. All work was done by myself. This ain't the first time I've installed complete trigger parts kits on CZ's.  A SP-01, Tactical, PCR and a P-01. I have full cofidence that this pistol will serve you well. But this is still considered a used pistol and is sold as-is. You are welcome to test fire the weapon at Johnson Creek Gun Club if you bring your own 9mm FACTORY (no reloads or remans)ammo.  I only ask there be no tire kickers.  If you have $900 in hand, let me know and lets make this happen.

The reduction in trigger reach and grip circumference increases concealability and enhances shooting ergonomics. Unlike some subcompact semiautomatic pistols that use a difficult to shoot "two-finger grip" frame, the USP Compact uses a narrow, full-hand grip frame with a choice of interchangeable extended or flush-fitting magazine floorplates. This makes the pistol easy to shoot without sacrificing concealability.The USP Compact is built to take the punishment of high-energy +P loads. To reduce the length of the slide and barrel on the USP Compact, the mechanical recoil reduction system found on large frame USPs has been replaced by a specially designed flat compression spring contained in the captive recoil spring assembly by a polymer absorber bushing. Service life is still engineered to exceed 20,000 rounds. Easy to shoot, simple to maintain; the USP Compact is a reliable, safe, accurate, and highly concealable pistol.

THIS IS THE MILITARY ISSUE FOR THE HUNGARIAN ARMY SIDE ARM ITS IN EXCELLENT  CONDITION HAVE FIRED SEVERAL TIMES I REALLY LIKE THE WAY IT FEELS VERY ACCURATE. 8+1, They are excellent guns, excellent trigger pull, It is almost an exact clone of a browning high power. Handgun Type: Semi-auto
Grip/Stock: Walnut
Made by KBI Inc/ FEG

A little history of this gun
Following World War II, the Browning Hi-Power became the leading military pistol in France, England and thoughout Western Europe and was copied behind the Iron Curtain in Eastern Europe. 
FEG of Hungary, the Hungarian national military arms manufacturer, copied the Browning Hi-Power 9mm design during the Cold War and supplied the Hungarian army with small arms. FEG also improved the BHP 9mm design by replacing the Browning Single-Action trigger (with its awful heavy pull) with a Double-Action/Single-Action trigger design copied from Smith & Wesson. 
KBI Inc. of Harrisburg, Pa., imported FEG Browning Hi-Power pistols into the U.S. starting in the 1980s, first the 9mm and later the FEG .45 ACP. The FEG .45 ACP GKK-45 has a DA/SA trigger and is a slightly larger version of the classic Browning Hi-Power in 9mm, scaled up for .45 ACP.
KBI Inc. is owner of Charles Daly and though it is no longer importing FEG pistols from Hungary, the company still provides parts and service for all FEG pistols KBI previously imported.

Questions I get asked most often: 

Can you kill a deer with it. If you are at point blank range, and shoot it in the eye, probably not. 

What is the bolt speed? Between 150 and 175 feet per second. 

How far is it accurate? Ive had people tell me up to 50 feet for small critters. 

Do you offer a warranty? No. There are a variety of factors that affect longevity including how you string it, and whether or not you pust the cocking handle all the way forward every time. 

What is the body made out of? Metal. Not cheap fiberglass like many and will last longer. The pieces that hold the cocking handle on are metal, as is the body, and they will withstand you forgetting to push the lever all the way forward more than the plastic body. 

Where can I get replacement strings - I carry them, usually. 

Where can I get extra bolts? I carry the metal ones, most of the time.

Are there instructions? Yes and dont be a dumbass and not follow them


Tips and tricks

title: For Sale:  Trapdoors NOT exempt from I-594
postcontent:
Trapdoors and practically EVERY other cartridge firing firearm are NOT exempt from i-594.  Read it (and weep!)

Quote:  Background checks would not be required for GIFTS between immediate family members or for antiques.

OK. So what's an antique?

Quote:   (...) a firearm or replica of a firearm not designed or redesigned for using rim fire or conventional center fire ignition with fixed ammunition and manufactured in or before 1898, including any matchlock, flintlock, percussion cap, or similar type of ignition system AND ALSO any firearm using fixed ammunition manufactured in or before 1898, for which ammunition is no longer manufactured in the United States and is not readily available in the ordinary channels of commercial trade.

That pretty much invalidates everything.  The intent of I-594 was to 
make virtually ALL "transfers" subject to a background check.  Mission accomplished.

A little history of this gun
Following World War II, the Browning Hi-Power became the leading military pistol in France, England and though out Western Europe and was copied behind the Iron Curtain in Eastern Europe. 
FEG of Hungary, the Hungarian national military arms manufacturer, copied the Browning Hi-Power 9mm design during the Cold War and supplied the Hungarian army with small arms. FEG also improved the BHP 9mm design by replacing the Browning Single-Action trigger (with its awful heavy pull) with a Double-Action/Single-Action trigger design copied from Smith & Wesson. 
KBI Inc. of Harrisburg, Pa., imported FEG Browning Hi-Power pistols into the U.S. starting in the 1980s, first the 9mm and later the FEG .45 ACP. The FEG .45 ACP GKK-45 has a DA/SA trigger and is a slightly larger version of the classic Browning Hi-Power in 9mm, scaled up for .45 ACP.
KBI Inc. is owner of Charles Daly and though it is no longer importing FEG pistols from Hungary, the company still provides parts and service for all FEG pistols KBI previously imported.

Wingo was an experimental indoor shooting sport invented by Winchester in the early 1970s. The only Wingo facility built was in San Diego, California.
The equipment consisted of a bank of machines that created four-inch diameter hollow spheres of ice. The player had a custom-made .20 calibre shotgun that was about the same size and weight as a .22 calibre rifle. The choice of calibre was to prevent players from bringing their own .22 calibre shells from outside. The gun was tethered to the shooting bench to prevent it from being pointed toward spectators and to facilitate the wiring for the internal microphone that detected when the gun was fired. Only about 20 of these guns were made and they are now very rare collector's items.
In the game, four-inch diameter hollow spheres of ice were fired toward the shooter from one of five ports from a distance of 75 feet. When the player fired the gun a number from 1 to 10 was presented by the scoring machine. The number depended on how quickly the player fired, higher numbers for quicker reactions. If the player hit the sphere he/she scored the number presented by the scoring machine.
Winchester conducted the trial in San Diego, rather than a midwest city where shooting sports were more popular, because they wanted to see if it would catch on in a city where there was an abundance of pastimes. The sport was not financially successful and the Wingo facility was closed in less than a year. The facility is now a branch of the San Diego Superior Court.

There is also a factory letter from Winchester authenticating this rifle.

title: For Sale/Trade:  SIG 556 Patrol SWAT with STS-081 Red dot & Swiss Handguards
location: (Downtown, but I'll travel to meet in WY), Cheyenne, Wyoming
postcontent:
Specs are available on Google for the technical folks... But let me say this. This is not your granpappy's 5.56! SIG took everything good about AK and AR combined together in a Swiss-accurate package with every single part being of premium materials and craftsmanship. Shoots WAY sub-MOA out of the box. It is not... at all.. comparable to an AR, besides caliber and magazine. It would be like trying to compare a 1999 Dodge Intrepid with a Ferrari Formula 1 car... yeah they both run on gas and have rubber tires... but that's about it.

Guys and gals: please, please ask me for photos of anything or any details you'd like to know prior to coming to see it. I want you to be a million percent happy with this. I'm so confident that you'll love it, go shoot it and if you're not sold, I'll buy it back on the spot. NOBODY ELSE SAYS THAT ABOUT A BATTLE RIFLE.

I'm available almost 24-7, so text me at 4O99398903 or email me through here! Hey, since it is the holidays, I'll consider trades and maybe a layaway. Let me know what you have.

Bought and maintained by a professional. It has ONE training/demo session of firing on it... 180 rds (just 6 mags), then my agency bought a boat-load of them and we were issued the select-fire and suppressed NFA variant, so this has been locked in the safe, fairly unused, besides showing it off to an unfriendly airport customer who thought you can drive a car on the runway... But hey, that's Wyoming, right?

History: (I first saw the 556 at a trade show and advocated my unit to use these) Purchased in 2013 from SIG to show my unit the capabilities of the SIG556, how fast it can be converted from carry-on baggage to operational platform and then changed from carbine to long-range DMR with scope. After that class/demo, it sat in a patrol aircraft (unfired) for a month, then I put it in the safe when our commercial order came in, now it is listed here.

-IMPORTANT: The trigger is tuned low, light and medium-length, so you can take up the first stage with nice even finger pressure and as you commit to the shot, only a further light pressure on the second stage will accurately send your shot. It's got to be about 2.5 to 3 lbs. (I don't have a gauge, but that's probably close) The second stage goes like glass: like a well tuned bolt action rifle. Out of the box, the trigger is more like a M9 pistol - Long and mysterious. Not any more.
-The desert wrap is NOT tape or sticky. It is cloth. If you don't like it, 10 seconds and gone.
-I'll throw in YOUR CHOICE of 2 Milspec, MagPul Pmag or SIG (linkable) 30-rd mags with fresh springs, caps and followers.
-I'll include a cool MagPul rounded trigger guard that I never installed.
-Swiss style handguards were installed because - let's face it - quad rails suck and chop your hands and gloves up, snagging all your gear and bags. Swiss handguards are the #1 requested mod for this weapon. ***The more ya know, right?!***
-The top swiss handguard was hastily Dremeled down (did not cut the metal heat shield) to accommodate that 56mm scope at the last second before the Unit Demo. It's invisible and under the desert wrap anyway.
-I will buy that $85.00 brand new swiss handguard if that dremel spot bothers you. It takes a while to come in, so it won't be available right away at time of sale, probably a few days later. Not a big deal! :)
-The white line on the safety lever was just for a range event yesterday and I've removed it. (I didn't shoot this rifle, but it was on the range with me, so I needed the marker for the range safety inspectors to see it at distance.)
-SIG-STS red dot is included, 56mm scope with rings are not, sorry.
-Blue OEM SIG case included ($149.00 value, yep, you can drop it on eBay for that much!)
-Papers, SIG decal & such included in the bluebox
-This model has the swiss/Glock round bayonet lug
-This model has a fixed front sight, flip-up backup iron sight and the red dot.
-Iron Zeroed at 300 (true BZO, not 33yd paper indoor target) with 75gr TAP/FPD
-Dot Zeroed for 1.25" high at 50 yds
-Extra CR2032 battery is stored in the handgrip for the red dot.
-This model has the real nice 1:7 twist barrel so you can shoot 55gr spam ammo or 100grain subsonics without tumbling or other accuracy problems that 1:9 (stock AR style barrels) are well known for.
-From field experience, you should use 75, 77 or 64 grain projectiles for maximum punch and accuracy if you are in a Zombie Removal Service situation. If you're just cleaning up prairie dogs from 1/4 mile away, 55grain ammo is OK to 650yds on a "man size" target. 55gr is so fast, it will vaporize Prairie dogs at short ranges, but not injure your average zombie size customer... use 55gr with due respect and careful shot placement. 
-Personally, We use Hornady TAP FPD, which is a round that is VERY easy to duplicate via reloading press: Lake City brass, Hornady .224 OTM HP projectile over a match primer and Varget powder.

BRASS TACKS GENTS: This is like the Rolex of battle rifles, and I'd bet my life on this thing. That's something I can't say about the M4A3 I was issued in Iraq and Durka-Durka-stan, or even the SCAR!

Guys, it's the holidays and EVERYONE deserves a Rolex once in their life... Why not make that Rolex your next battle rifle? Unlike an AR platform, the SIG 556 WILL complete the 2500 round torture test without carbon fouling failure. At about 2300 rounds, the gas selector will need to be switched to position 2, but that's it. I've personally seen the test, the SIG instructor was "chump confident" and almost mathematically, his numbers were always right on. to be honest, I wanted him to be wrong just because he was such a snob, but nope, it was smoking, sometimes even glowing and still running like a dang clock. THIS RIFLE WAS NOT TORTURED IN ANY WAY. it only has 180 rounds through it. (The class used factory owned rifles for testing)


I'm not a dealer, this is a private sale, so of course, Wyoming FTF rules apply (be a WY resident, not a chump... etc.)
